        "canonical_link": "https://imdb2.freeforums.net/thread/85575/southern-gothic%3Fpage%3D1",
        "text": "Post by petrolino on\n\nMary Flannery O'Connor American writer and essayist was a Southern writer who wrote in a Southern Gothic style, using regional settings portraying grotesque characters, her writings examined questions of morality and ethics, she masterly combined the comic with the tragic.\n\nWise Blood is the first novel by Flannery O'Connor it was published in 1952. Themes of redemption, racism, sexism, and isolation run through the novel. O'Connor stated that the book is about freedom, free will, life and death, and the inevitability of belief. The novel has become a classic of twentieth-century literature.\n\nWise Blood (1979) directed by John Huston is an original and offbeat tale, faithful to the spirit of the book set in the Deep South during the post-war era. This brilliant adaptation is a savage satire, a parody of existentialism, a grim view of American secular and commercial culture...\n\nCritically acclaimed, Wise Blood unfortunately went over the heads of most audiences and was not successful at the box office .\n\nIt's been so many since I've seen 'Wise Blood'. I just got paid end of last month so I might try and pick up the dvd release from Screenbound Pictures. I like it a great deal, it's probably my favourite of John Huston's post-1970 films. Brad Dourif and Amy Wright are incredible. I'd really like to see 'Phobia' (1980) too though, from the final phase of Huston's directorial career.\n\nPost by petrolino on\n\nAlso,--and I hope this hasn't been mentioned yet--another Faulkner adaptation, this one from 1949, the Clarence Brown film of [Intruder In The Dust.\n\nGlad you mentioned Intruder In the Dust (1949). It crossed my mind, but I wasn't sure it applied (I always associate \"Southern Gothic\" with a quality of elegantly faded grandeur, but perhaps I'm off-base). IITD does have its Gothic elements (the tense nighttime scene at the grave, for instance) and it's decidedly and authentically Southern.\n\nEither way, it's a beautifully-realized film, stark and arresting, and one which sneaks up on viewers, beginning modestly matter-of-fact before subtly pulling them in as inexorably as that bog below the bridge, and delivering a series of gut-wrenching punches once it has done so. Brown was at the absolute top of his game, and it's one I'd recommend to anyone.\n\nWhat do you both think about some of the crime writers who've been regularly adapted for screen being described as \"southern gothic\" writers? As I understand it, writers like Faulkner and Williams were inspired to a degree by American crime and horror writers who'd come before. A bit later, you have someone like Elmore Leonard who seems to absorb gothic elements in some of his work and came from New Orleans, Louisiana, like Truman Capote. Or pulp writer Charles Willeford who was from Little Rock, Arkansas, and like Leonard, contributed to popularising Florida crime stories in the 20th century."
